{"title_page": "Patrick Queen", "text_new": "{{short description|American football middle linebacker}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n| name            = Patrick Queen\n| image           = Patrick Queen LSU2019.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| caption         =Queen at LSU in 2019\n| school          = LSU Tigers\n| currentnumber   = 8\n| currentposition = [[Middle linebacker]]\n| class           = Junior\n| pastschools     = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (2017\u20132019)\n| bowlgames       = \n*[[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)]]\n*[[2019 Peach Bowl]]\n*[[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]\n| highschool      = [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1999|8|13}}\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 1\n| weight_lb       = 227\n| highlights      = \n*[[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n|espn=4242207\n}}\n'''Patrick Queen''' is an American [[college football]] [[middle linebacker]] for the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nQueen grew up in [[Ventress, Louisiana]] and attended [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]], where he played both linebacker and running back.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_6d330be4-daf4-11e9-9156-17a9adfadaa7.html|title=Patrick Queen is the 'miracle baby' dedicated to LSU from birth; 'One of our best players'|last=Kubena|first=Brooks|date=September 20, 2019|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> As a senior, he rushed for 1,487 yards and 19 touchdowns on offense and had 66 tackles, seven tackles for losses, and six passes broken up on defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2020/01/13/eye-title-patrick-queen-parents-coaches-reflect-lsu-lbs-legendary-career-livonia-high-school/|title=EYE ON THE TITLE: Patrick Queen, parents, and coaches reflect on LSU LB\u2019s legendary career at Livonia High School|last=Doucet|first=Jacques|date=January 13, 2020|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n[[File:2020-0113-OrgeronBurrowQueen.PNG|thumb|left|200px|Queen at the post-game presser for the 2020 National Championship game where he was named Defensive MVP.]]\nQueen made six tackles in 12 games played as a true freshman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_b0830fa8-d716-11e8-a4e1-37c6795bf4db.html|title=LSU's Patrick Queen tops rotation in Devin White's place; Garrett Brumfield works out; other practice notes|last=Rabalais|first=Scott|date=October 23, 2018|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> He finished his sophomore season with 40 tackles, 5.0 tackles for loss and a sack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1377511/2019/11/14/lsu-football-linebacker-patrick-queen-patience-ole-miss/|title=\u2018I\u2019ve never met anybody who wants it more than he does\u2019: Appreciating the patience of Patrick Queen|last=Miller|first=Brody|date=November 14, 2019|website=[[The Athletic]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen entered his junior year on the watchlist for the Butkus Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2019/07/22/lsu-leads-nation-with-linebackers-named-butkus-award-watch-list/|title=LSU leads nation with 4 linebackers named to Butkus Award Watch List|last=Auzenne|first=Josh|date=July 22, 2019|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen finished the regular season with 69 tackles (eight for a loss), 2.5 sacks, three pass deflections, two breakups, an interception and a fumble recovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/oklahoma/Article/Patrick-Queen-bulletin-board-material-LSU-Tigers-College-Football-Playoff-141095375/|title=LSU\u2019s Queen: OU O-line, backs not great, \"going to dominate\"|last=Helmer|first=Joey|date=December 26, 2019|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Queen was named the Defensive MVP of the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]] after making eight tackles with 2.5 for a loss and a combined sack against Clemson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_447132ee-367f-11ea-af81-335a5a48c669.html|title=Patrick Queen-led defense helps LSU fend off Clemson|last=Just|first=Amie|date=January 13, 2020|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Following the end of the season Queen announced that he would forgo his senior season to enter the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/lsu/Article/LSU-Football-Patrick-Queen-NFL-Draft-2020-decision-142245053/|title=Patrick Queen declares for 2020 NFL Draft|last=Embody|first=Billy|date=January 15, 2020|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://lsusports.net/sports/football/roster/patrick-queen/20292 LSU Tigers bio]\n\n{{2019 LSU Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen, Patrick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:People from Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football middle linebacker}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n| name            = Patrick Queen\n| image           = Patrick Queen LSU2019.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| caption         =Queen at LSU in 2019\n| school          = LSU Tigers\n| currentnumber   = 8\n| currentposition = [[Middle linebacker]]\n| class           = Junior\n| pastschools     = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (2017\u20132019)\n| bowlgames       = \n*[[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)]]\n*[[2019 Peach Bowl]]\n*[[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]\n| highschool      = [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1999|8|13}}\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 1\n| weight_lb       = 227\n| highlights      = \n*[[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n|espn=4242207\n}}\n'''Patrick Queen''' is an American [[college football]] [[middle linebacker]] for the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nQueen grew up in [[Ventress, Louisiana]] and attended [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]], where he played both linebacker and running back.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_6d330be4-daf4-11e9-9156-17a9adfadaa7.html|title=Patrick Queen is the 'miracle baby' dedicated to LSU from birth; 'One of our best players'|last=Kubena|first=Brooks|date=September 20, 2019|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> As a senior, he rushed for 1,487 yards and 19 touchdowns on offense and had 66 tackles, seven tackles for losses, and six passes broken up on defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2020/01/13/eye-title-patrick-queen-parents-coaches-reflect-lsu-lbs-legendary-career-livonia-high-school/|title=EYE ON THE TITLE: Patrick Queen, parents, and coaches reflect on LSU LB\u2019s legendary career at Livonia High School|last=Doucet|first=Jacques|date=January 13, 2020|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n[[File:2020-0113-OrgeronBurrowQueen.PNG|thumb|left|200px|Queen at the post-game presser for the 2020 National Championship game where he was named Defensive MVP.]]\nQueen made six tackles in 12 games played as a true freshman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_b0830fa8-d716-11e8-a4e1-37c6795bf4db.html|title=LSU's Patrick Queen tops rotation in Devin White's place; Garrett Brumfield works out; other practice notes|last=Rabalais|first=Scott|date=October 23, 2018|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> He finished his sophomore season with 40 tackles, 5.0 tackles for loss and a sack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1377511/2019/11/14/lsu-football-linebacker-patrick-queen-patience-ole-miss/|title=\u2018I\u2019ve never met anybody who wants it more than he does\u2019: Appreciating the patience of Patrick Queen|last=Miller|first=Brody|date=November 14, 2019|website=[[The Athletic]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen entered his junior year on the watchlist for the Butkus Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2019/07/22/lsu-leads-nation-with-linebackers-named-butkus-award-watch-list/|title=LSU leads nation with 4 linebackers named to Butkus Award Watch List|last=Auzenne|first=Josh|date=July 22, 2019|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen finished the regular season with 69 tackles (eight for a loss), 2.5 sacks, three pass deflections, two breakups, an interception and a fumble recovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/oklahoma/Article/Patrick-Queen-bulletin-board-material-LSU-Tigers-College-Football-Playoff-141095375/|title=LSU\u2019s Queen: OU O-line, backs not great, \"going to dominate\"|last=Helmer|first=Joey|date=December 26, 2019|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Queen was named the Defensive MVP of the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]] after making eight tackles with 2.5 for a loss and a combined sack against Clemson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_447132ee-367f-11ea-af81-335a5a48c669.html|title=Patrick Queen-led defense helps LSU fend off Clemson|last=Just|first=Amie|date=January 13, 2020|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Following the end of the season Queen announced that he would forgo his senior season to enter the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/lsu/Article/LSU-Football-Patrick-Queen-NFL-Draft-2020-decision-142245053/|title=Patrick Queen declares for 2020 NFL Draft|last=Embody|first=Billy|date=January 15, 2020|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://lsusports.net/sports/football/roster/patrick-queen/20292 LSU Tigers bio]\n\n{{2019 LSU Tigers football navbox}}\n\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:People from Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Queen"}
{"title_page": "June 15", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[763 BC]] &ndash; [[Assyria]]ns record a [[Assyrian eclipse|solar eclipse]] that is later used to fix the [[chronology]] of [[Mesopotamia]]n history.\n* [[844]] &ndash; [[Louis II of Italy|Louis II]] is crowned as king of [[Italy]] at [[Rome]] by pope [[Pope Sergius II|Sergius II]].\n* [[923]] &ndash; [[Battle of Soissons (923)|Battle of Soissons]]: King [[Robert I of France]] is killed and King [[Charles the Simple]] is arrested by the supporters of Duke [[Rudolph of France|Rudolph of Burgundy]].\n*[[1184]] &ndash; King [[Magnus V of Norway]] is killed at the [[Battle of Fimreite]].\n*[[1215]] &ndash; King [[John of England]] puts his [[seal (emblem)|seal]] to [[Magna Carta]].\n*[[1219]] &ndash; [[Northern Crusades]]: Danish victory at the [[Battle of Lyndanisse|Battle of Lindanise]] (modern-day [[Tallinn]]) establishes the Danish [[Danish Estonia|Duchy of Estonia]]. \n*[[1246]] &ndash; With the death of [[Frederick II, Duke of Austria]], the [[Babenberg dynasty]] ends in Austria.\n*[[1300]] &ndash; The city of [[Bilbao]] is founded.\n*[[1312]] &ndash; At the [[Battle of Rozgony]], King [[Charles I of Hungary]] wins a decisive victory over the family of [[Palatine of Hungary|Palatine]] [[Amade Aba]].\n*[[1389]] &ndash; [[Battle of Kosovo]]: The [[Ottoman Empire]] defeats [[Serbs]] and [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]]ns.\n*[[1410]] &ndash; In a decisive [[Yongle Emperor's campaigns against the Mongols|battle at Onon River]], the Mongol forces of [[Oljei Temur]] were decimated by the Chinese armies of the [[Yongle Emperor]].\n*[[1502]] &ndash; [[Christopher Columbus]] lands on the island of [[Martinique]] on his fourth voyage.\n*[[1520]] &ndash; [[Pope Leo X]] threatens to [[Excommunication|excommunicate]] [[Martin Luther]] in ''[[Exsurge Domine]]''.\n*[[1648]] &ndash; [[Margaret Jones (Puritan midwife)|Margaret Jones]] is hanged in [[Boston]] for [[witchcraft]] in the first such execution for the [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]].\n*[[1667]] &ndash; The first human [[blood transfusion]] is administered by Dr. [[Jean-Baptiste Denys]].\n*[[1670]] &ndash; The first stone of [[Fort Ricasoli]] is laid down in Malta.\n*[[1752]] &ndash; [[Benjamin Franklin]] proves that [[lightning]] is [[electricity]] (traditional date, the exact date is unknown).\n*[[1776]] &ndash; Delaware Separation Day: [[Delaware]] votes to suspend government under the British Crown and separate officially from [[Pennsylvania]].\n*[[1800]] &ndash; The [[Provisional Army of the United States]] is dissolved. \n*[[1804]] &ndash; [[New Hampshire]] approves the [[Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], ratifying the document.\n*[[1808]] &ndash; [[Joseph Bonaparte]] becomes [[King of Spain]].\n*[[1836]] &ndash; [[Arkansas]] is admitted as the 25th [[U.S. state]].\n*[[1844]] &ndash; [[Charles Goodyear]] receives a [[patent]] for [[vulcanization]], a process to strengthen [[rubber]].\n*[[1846]] &ndash; The [[Oregon Treaty]] establishes the [[49th parallel north|49th parallel]] as the border between the United States and Canada, from the [[Rocky Mountains]] to the [[Strait of Juan de Fuca]].\n*[[1859]] &ndash; [[Pig War (1859)|Pig War]]: Ambiguity in the Oregon Treaty leads to the \"Northwestern Boundary Dispute\" between United States and British/Canadian settlers.\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: The [[Second Battle of Petersburg]] begins.\n*  1864   &ndash; [[Arlington National Cemetery]] is established when {{convert|200|acre|km2}} of the Arlington estate (formerly owned by Confederate General [[Robert E. Lee]]) are officially set aside as a military [[cemetery]] by [[United States Secretary of War|U.S. Secretary of War]] [[Edwin M. Stanton]].<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Harrow|first=Robert Jr.|title=The Quartermaster: Montgomery C. Meigs, Lincoln's General, Master Builder of the Union Army|location=New York|publisher=Simon & Schuster|date=2016|isbn=9781451671926|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a2c6DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=206\u2013207, 282|postscript=none}}; {{cite book|last=Poole|first=Robert M.|title=On Hallowed Ground: The Story of Arlington National Cemetery|location=New York|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|date=2010|isbn=9780802715494|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ec-mCAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=281}}</ref>\n*[[1877]] &ndash; [[Henry Ossian Flipper]] becomes the first [[African American]] cadet to graduate from the [[United States Military Academy]].\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Eadweard Muybridge]] takes [[Sallie Gardner at a Gallop|a series of photographs]] to prove that all four feet of a horse leave the ground when it runs; the study becomes the basis of [[film|motion pictures]].\n*[[1888]] &ndash; Crown Prince [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor|Wilhelm]] becomes Kaiser Wilhelm II; he will be the last Emperor of the [[German Empire]]. Due to the death of his predecessors [[William I, German Emperor|Wilhelm I]] and [[Frederick III, German Emperor|Frederick III]], 1888 is the [[Year of the Three Emperors]].\n*[[1896]] &ndash; The [[1896 Sanriku earthquake|deadliest tsunami]] in Japan's history kills more than 22,000 people.\n*[[1904]] &ndash; A fire aboard the steamboat {{SS|General Slocum}} in New York City's [[East River]] kills 1,000.\n*[[1916]] &ndash; United States President [[Woodrow Wilson]] signs a bill incorporating the [[Boy Scouts of America]], making them the only American youth organization with a federal charter.\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[John Alcock (aviator)|John Alcock]] and [[Arthur Brown (aviator)|Arthur Brown]] complete the first nonstop [[Transatlantic flight of Alcock and Brown|transatlantic flight]] when they reach [[Clifden]], [[County Galway]], Ireland.\n*[[1920]] &ndash; A new border treaty between Germany and Denmark gives northern [[Duchy of Schleswig|Schleswig]] to Denmark.\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Bessie Coleman]] earns her pilot's license, becoming the first female pilot of African-American descent.\n*[[1934]] &ndash; The United States [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]] is founded.\n*[[1936]] &ndash; First flight of the [[Vickers Wellington]] bomber.\n*[[1937]] &ndash; A German expedition led by [[Karl Wien]] loses sixteen members in an [[avalanche]] on [[Nanga Parbat]]. It is the worst single disaster to occur on an [[Eight-thousander|8000m peak]].\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[Operation Ariel]] begins: [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] troops start to evacuate France, following Germany's takeover of Paris and most of the nation.\n*[[1944]] &ndash; World War II: [[Battle of Saipan]]: The United States invade Japanese-occupied [[Saipan]].\n*  1944   &ndash; In the [[1944 Saskatchewan general election|Saskatchewan general election]], the [[Co-operative Commonwealth Federation|CCF]], led by [[Tommy Douglas]], is elected and forms the first [[Socialism|socialist]] government in North America.\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[Charles Manson]] goes on trial for the [[Sharon Tate]] murders.\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Red Army Faction]] co-founder [[Ulrike Meinhof]] is captured by police in [[Langenhagen]].\n*[[1977]] &ndash; After the death of dictator [[Francisco Franco]] in 1975, the first democratic elections took place in [[Spain]] on this day.\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Hussein of Jordan|King Hussein]] of [[Jordan]] marries American Lisa Halaby, who takes the name [[Queen Noor of Jordan|Queen Noor]].\n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Rembrandt]]'s painting ''[[Dana\u00eb (Rembrandt painting)|Dana\u00eb]]'' is attacked by a man (later judged insane) who throws [[sulfuric acid]] on the canvas and cuts it twice with a knife.\n*[[1991]] &ndash; In the Philippines, [[Mount Pinatubo]] erupts in the [[1991 eruption of Mount Pinatubo|second largest volcanic eruption of the 20th century]], killing over 800 people.\n*[[1992]] &ndash; The [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] rules in ''[[United States v. Alvarez-Machain|United States v. \u00c1lvarez-Macha\u00edn]]'' that it is permissible for the United States to forcibly extradite suspects in foreign countries and bring them to the United States for trial, without approval from those other countries.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Israel]] and [[Vatican City]] establish full [[diplomatic relations]].\n*[[1996]] &ndash; [[The Troubles]]: The [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) detonates [[1996 Manchester bombing|a powerful truck bomb]] in the middle of Manchester, England, devastating the [[Manchester city centre|city centre]] and injuring 200 people.\n*[[2001]] &ndash; Leaders of the People's Republic of China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan and Uzbekistan formed the [[Shanghai Cooperation Organisation]].\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[Nik Wallenda]] becomes the first person to successfully [[Tightrope walking|tightrope walk]] directly over [[Niagara Falls]].\n*[[2013]] &ndash; A [[June 2013 Quetta bombing|bomb explodes]] on a bus in the [[Pakistani]] city of [[Quetta]], killing at least 25 people and wounding 22 others.\n<!--Do NOT add video games, video game consoles, movie, TV or album releases, as they WILL be deleted-->\n\n==Births==\n*[[1330]] &ndash; [[Edward, the Black Prince]] of England (d. 1376)\n*[[1423]] &ndash; [[Gabriele Sforza]], Archbishop of Milan (d. 1457)\n*[[1479]] &ndash; [[Lisa del Giocondo]], Italian model, subject of the ''[[Mona Lisa]]'' (d. 1542)\n*[[1519]] &ndash; [[Henry FitzRoy, 1st Duke of Richmond and Somerset]], English politician, [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]] (d. 1536)\n*[[1542]] &ndash; [[Richard Grenville]], English captain and explorer (d. 1591)\n*[[1549]] &ndash; [[Elizabeth Knollys]], English noblewoman (d. 1605)\n*[[1553]] &ndash; [[Archduke Ernest of Austria]] (d. 1595)\n*[[1605]] &ndash; [[Thomas Randolph (poet)|Thomas Randolph]], English poet and playwright (d. 1635)\n*[[1618]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Blondel]], French architect (d. 1686)\n*[[1623]] &ndash; [[Cornelis de Witt]], Dutch politician (d. 1672)\n*[[1624]] &ndash; [[Hiob Ludolf]], German orientalist and philologist (d. 1704)\n*[[1640]] &ndash; [[Bernard Lamy]], French mathematician and theologian (d. 1715)\n*[[1645]] &ndash; [[Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin]], English politician (d. 1712)\n*[[1749]] &ndash; [[Georg Joseph Vogler]], German organist, composer, and theorist (d. 1814)\n*[[1754]] &ndash; [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Elhuyar]], Spanish chemist and mineralogist (d. 1796)\n*[[1755]] &ndash; [[Antoine Fran\u00e7ois, comte de Fourcroy]], French chemist and entomologist (d. 1809)\n*[[1763]] &ndash; [[Franz Danzi]], German cellist, composer, and conductor (d. 1826)\n*  1763   &ndash; [[Kobayashi Issa]], Japanese priest and poet (d. 1827)\n*[[1765]] &ndash; [[Martin Baum]], American businessman and politician, [[List of mayors of Cincinnati|Mayor of Cincinnati]] (d. 1831)\n*  1765   &ndash; [[Johann Gottlieb Friedrich von Bohnenberger]], German astronomer and mathematician (d. 1831)\n*[[1767]] &ndash; [[Rachel Jackson]], American wife of [[Andrew Jackson]] (d. 1828)\n*[[1777]] &ndash; [[David Daniel Davis]], Welsh physician and academic (d. 1841)\n*[[1789]] &ndash; [[Josiah Henson]], American minister, author, and activist (d. 1883)\n*[[1792]] &ndash; [[Thomas Mitchell (explorer)|Thomas Mitchell]], Scottish-Australian colonel and explorer (d. 1855)\n*[[1801]] &ndash; [[Benjamin Wright Raymond]], American merchant and politician, 3rd [[Mayor of Chicago]] (d. 1883)\n*[[1805]] &ndash; [[William B. Ogden]], American businessman and politician, 1st [[Mayor of Chicago]] (d. 1877)\n*[[1809]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Garneau]], Canadian poet and historian (d. 1866)\n*[[1835]] &ndash; [[Adah Isaacs Menken]], American actress, painter, and poet (d. 1868)\n*[[1843]] &ndash; [[Edvard Grieg]], Norwegian pianist and composer (d. 1907)\n*[[1848]] &ndash; [[Gheevarghese Mar Gregorios of Parumala]], Indian bishop and saint (d. 1902)\n*[[1872]] &ndash; [[Thomas William Burgess]], English swimmer and water polo player (d. 1950)\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Herman Smith-Johannsen]], Norwegian-Canadian skier (d. 1987)\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Margaret Abbott]], Indian-American golfer (d. 1955)<ref>{{cite news | last=Fox | first=Margalit | title=Margaret Abbott, an Unwitting Olympic Trailblazer | date=March 8, 2018 | newspaper=The New York Times | url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/obituaries/overlooked-margaret-abbott.html | accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Kesago Nakajima]], Japanese lieutenant general in the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] (d. 1945)\n*[[1884]] &ndash; [[Harry Langdon]], American actor, director, and screenwriter (d. 1944)\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Frank Clement (racing driver)|Frank Clement]], British racing driver (d. 1970)\n*[[1888]] &ndash; [[Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Velarde]], Mexican poet and author (d. 1921)\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[Georg W\u00fcst]], German oceanographer and academic (d. 1977)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Robert Russell Bennett]], American composer and conductor (d. 1981)\n*  1894   &ndash; [[Nikolai Chebotaryov]], Ukrainian-Russian mathematician and theorist (d. 1947)\n*[[1898]] &ndash; [[Hubertus Strughold]], German-American physiologist and academic (d. 1986)\n*[[1900]] &ndash; [[Gotthard G\u00fcnther]], German philosopher and academic (d. 1984)\n*  1900   &ndash; [[Otto Luening]], German-American composer and conductor (d. 1996)\n*[[1901]] &ndash; [[Elmar Lohk]], Russian-Estonian architect (d. 1963)\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[Erik Erikson]], German-American psychologist and psychoanalyst (d. 1994)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Gordon Welchman]], English-American mathematician and author (d. 1985)\n*  1906   &ndash; [[L\u00e9on Degrelle]], Belgian [[SS]] officer (d. 1994)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[James Robertson Justice]], English actor and educator (d. 1975)\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Elena Nikolaidi]], Greek-American soprano and educator (d. 2002)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[David Rose (songwriter)|David Rose]], English-American pianist, composer, and conductor (d. 1990)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Wilbert Awdry]], English author, co-created [[Thomas the Tank Engine]] (d. 1997)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Tom Adair]], American songwriter, composer, and screenwriter (d. 1988)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Yuri Andropov]], Russian politician (d. 1984)\n*  1914   &ndash; [[Saul Steinberg]], Romanian-American cartoonist (d. 1999)\n*  1914   &ndash; [[Hilda Terry]], American cartoonist (d. 2006)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Nini Theilade]], Danish ballet dancer, choreographer, and educator (d. 2018)\n*  1915   &ndash; [[Thomas Huckle Weller]], American biologist and virologist, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2008)\n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Olga Erteszek]], Polish-American fashion designer (d. 1989)\n*  1916   &ndash; [[Horacio Salg\u00e1n]], Argentinian pianist, composer, and conductor (d. 2016)\n*  1916   &ndash; [[Herbert A. Simon]], American political scientist and economist, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2001)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[John Fenn (chemist)|John Fenn]], American chemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2010)\n*  1917   &ndash; [[Michalis Genitsaris]], Greek singer-songwriter (d. 2005)\n*  1917   &ndash; [[Lash LaRue]], American actor and producer (d. 1996)<ref>{{cite book|author1=Arthur F. McClure|author2=Ken D. Jones|title=Western Films: Heroes, Heavies and Sagebrush of the \"B\" Genre|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6EqAAAAYAAJ|year=1972|publisher=A.S. Barnes & Company}}</ref>\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Tombalbaye]], Chadian politician, 1st [[President of Chad]] (d. 1975)<ref>{{cite book|title=Africa: a handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8_sEAQAAIAAJ|year=1973}}</ref>\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Keith Andrews (racing driver)|Keith Andrews]], American racing driver (d. 1957)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Alla Kazanskaya]], Russian actress (d. 2008)